<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-449-130  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 449 130.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  July 1989 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Made to measure? (application of Computer Integrated Manufacturingsystems to the textile industry; includes related article onavailable software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Roberts, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Integration of production and machine control systems with manualoperations in the textile industry can lead to more efficientoperation.andP;  Computer Integrated Manufacturing (CIM) systems mustcombine technical and commercial data so, for example, physicalstock could be compared with product demand and then used todetermine the amount of time to run the looms.andP;  The costeffectiveness of any control system should be carefully evaluated,though, to be sure the process and type of machines will lendthemselves to an integrated data approach.andP;  Packaged software fortextile production control is scare and little coordination existsbetween supplies.andP;  Ideally a CIM textile system would use computeraided design; measuring, recipe production and dyeing controlsystems; and machine monitoring and production planning systems.andO;Several hypothetical examples of a successful integrated approachare given.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Textile IndustryComputer-Integrated ManufacturingIntegrated ApproachControl SystemsManagement.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Weaving systems together: the benefits of integration. (table)Tying manual operations to computer-based systems. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>